<h2>The Question</h2>
<p>
    <a href="/backlog/094-ai-upgrader-tools/">#094</a>'s upgrader MVP built the
    <strong>legacy&nbsp;→&nbsp;standard</strong> upgrade kind. <a href="/backlog/191-upgrader-version-migration-codemods/">#191</a>
    is the <strong>second kind</strong> — <em>across standard / dependency versions</em>: apply
    breaking-change codemods when a protocol, adapter, or provider contract evolves, so "upgrade to the new
    version" doesn't mean hand-editing every call site. #191's body had deferred itself, blocked on a
    machine-readable change/migration descriptor format. This survey re-grounds it now that the blockers are
    resolved, asking <strong>how the version-migration mode consumes the descriptor and applies
    transforms</strong>, per design-first step&nbsp;1.
</p>

<h2>Recommendation (forks in #191)</h2>
<ol>
    <li><strong>A mode of the existing engine, not a separate tool</strong> — the version-migration upgrader
        is an <strong>input adapter + mode of <a href="/backlog/094-ai-upgrader-tools/">#094</a>'s
        <code>upgraderEngine</code></strong> (same analyze&nbsp;→&nbsp;transform&nbsp;→&nbsp;<code>verifyUpgrade</code>
        arc, same <code>CustomAnalyzerRegistry</code> seam), differing only in input: an already-conformant
        source + a <code>changelog-manifest</code> delta, not legacy code. <em>Medium-high confidence.</em></li>
    <li><strong>Declarative-first, imperative escape hatch</strong> — a migration entry describes the transform
        declaratively for mechanical changes (renamed attribute, moved intent dimension, retired provider id),
        and references an imperative codemod only when the change is too complex to declare. OpenRewrite's
        ruling principle, and the most-permissive default (the migration-script reference is optional).
        <em>Medium confidence.</em></li>
    <li><strong>Ratify, not forks</strong> — the descriptor <em>format</em> is the resolved
        <a href="/protocols/#protocol-changelog-manifest">changelog-manifest protocol</a> (#102); the
        <em>safety gate</em> is #094's <code>verifyUpgrade</code>. Consume both; design neither anew.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Finding 1 — both prerequisites #191 named already shipped</h2>
<p>
    #191 said it needed (a) a machine-readable migration descriptor and (b) the verify gate + provider shape.
    Both exist. The descriptor is the <strong>changelog-manifest protocol</strong>
    (<a href="/protocols/#protocol-changelog-manifest">protocols.json</a>, <a href="/backlog/102-changelog-manifest-standard/">#102</a>,
    resolved): per-module entries keyed to a semver severity + Keep-a-Changelog type, <strong>plus a migration
    linkage</strong> — a breaking entry references the codemod that applies it, with author + integrity-hash
    trust metadata so the pipeline can verify a migration before running it. It is explicitly "consumed by
    upgraders (#094)." The engine is <strong>#094's <code>upgraderEngine</code></strong> —
    <code>verifyUpgrade</code> (re-parse + round-trip + conformance), the <code>upgrade()</code> orchestrator,
    and the <code>CustomAnalyzerRegistry</code> provider seam. <a href="/backlog/266-validation-capability-manifest-schema-semver-scheme-ratify-o/">#266</a>
    added the semver/availability axis (<code>compareSpecVersions</code>, <code>featureAvailableIn</code>,
    <code>FEATURE_SINCE</code>). So #191 is <strong>wiring plus two design calls</strong>, not greenfield.
</p>

<h2>Finding 2 — Angular <code>ng update</code> is the canonical version-gated migration runner</h2>
<p>
    A library ships a <a href="https://angular.love/angular-schematics-deep-dive-part-4-writing-migration-schematics-with-ng-update"><code>migrations.json</code></a>
    (registered under <code>package.json</code> <code>ng-update.migrations</code>); each entry is
    <code>{version, factory, description}</code>, the <code>factory</code> pointing to a transform that
    returns a <code>Rule</code>. <code>ng update</code> runs every migration whose <code>version</code> falls
    in <code>&gt;installedVersion, &lt;=targetVersion</code> — <strong>in order, across intermediate
    versions</strong>. This is exactly the shape #191 needs: the <code>changelog-manifest</code> is the
    <code>migrations.json</code> analog (per-release, per-module, migration reference); the version-gated,
    ordered, intermediate-spanning <em>run</em> is the mode's core loop, and the range gating maps onto #266's
    <code>compareSpecVersions</code>.
</p>

<h2>Finding 3 — OpenRewrite settles the declarative-vs-imperative axis</h2>
<p>
    <a href="https://docs.openrewrite.org/authoring-recipes/types-of-recipes">OpenRewrite</a> offers three
    recipe types — declarative (YAML, compose existing recipes + light config), refaster (templates), and
    imperative (extend <code>Recipe</code> for full AST control) — under an explicit principle: <strong>"if it
    can be declarative, make it declarative; use imperative only when necessary."</strong> That is Fork 2's
    recommended default verbatim. A renamed attribute or retired provider id is a declarative descriptor the
    engine interprets; only a transform with real nuance references an imperative codemod. The
    <code>changelog-manifest</code>'s migration-script reference being <em>optional</em> is what makes the
    declarative-first / imperative-fallback split expressible in the existing protocol.
</p>

<h2>Finding 4 — the verify gate is WE's differentiator over the incumbents</h2>
<p>
    Angular schematics and <a href="https://github.com/facebook/jscodeshift">jscodeshift</a> apply transforms
    but <strong>don't verify</strong> the result conforms — they trust the codemod. #094's
    <code>verifyUpgrade</code> (re-parse + round-trip fidelity + intent conformance) is reused here: a migrated
    call site is <em>offered</em> only if it still parses and conforms. This is the
    <a href="/backlog/089-monetization-product-ideas/">#089</a> "propose-and-verify" moat applied to version
    migration — incumbents bump versions or run codemods, but only a verifiable target turns a transform into
    a trustworthy one. It is also why this is not Renovate/Dependabot: those bump versions; #191 applies
    semantic breaking-change codemods gated by conformance.
</p>

<h2>Finding 5 — the item splits cleanly once ratified</h2>
<p>
    With both forks decided, #191 (size&nbsp;8) splits into agent-ready builds: <strong>(a)</strong> the
    <code>changelog-manifest</code> consumption + version-gated migration planner (range select + order);
    <strong>(b)</strong> the declarative transform interpreter + imperative-codemod escape hatch;
    <strong>(c)</strong> the version-migration input adapter/mode on <code>upgraderEngine</code> with
    <code>verifyUpgrade</code> wiring. These graduate via a <code>blockedBy</code> chain in that order — a
    prepared decision yields agent-ready builds, not code itself.
</p>

